{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bf3bada5-caf7-42f0-87ba-86189d34f905","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. No extra tooling needed.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**To also get a core dump**, run this *before* launching your app:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nCore dumps land in `/cores/` (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` file contains the native backtrace with addresses. If you have the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill or `atos`, you can symbolicate the frames back to .NET runtime source lines.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4de500e7-2120-415c-b9be-5deabb58bdc5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase.\n\nOn macOS, when a process crashes, the system automatically generates a crash report (`.ips` file). These are stored in:\n\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user-launched processes)\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-level processes)\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, since `createdump` isn't bundled, you rely on macOS's built-in crash reporting. You can also enable core dumps via `ulimit -c unlimited`.\n\n\nI'll provide a straightforward answer about where to find these crash reports and how to access them.","outputTokens":395,"requestId":"980F:1B2DC6:B81CDC:D87785:69F40645"},"id":"ca896097-eab3-4987-8202-75a81810680f","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:47:59.658Z","parentId":"b4975745-ff9d-4bca-9910-6db15fe40195"}
